# Coding Standards

## TypeScript

- Strict mode is enabled — no `any` unless justified with a comment
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object shapes; use `type` for unions/intersections
- Export types/interfaces from the file where they are defined
- Never use `// @ts-ignore` — fix the underlying type issue

## Components

- One component per file; filename matches the exported name (PascalCase)
- Use named exports for all components except page/layout route files (those use default)
- Define props interface directly above or inline with the component
- Server Components are the default — only add `'use client'` when genuinely needed

## Server vs Client Components

```
Server Component  → data fetching, translations via getTranslations, no hooks
Client Component  → useState, useEffect, useTheme, useRouter, browser APIs
```

Keep Client Components small. Push interactivity down to leaf nodes; render the static shell on the server.

## Import Order

1. External packages (`react`, `next`, `next-intl`, etc.)
2. Internal `@/` path aliases
3. Relative imports (only within the same feature folder)

## Naming

- Components: `PascalCase`
- Functions/variables: `camelCase`
- Constants: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` for true constants; `camelCase` for config objects
- Files: `PascalCase` for components, `camelCase` for utilities and hooks

## Don't

- Don't add error handling for impossible cases
- Don't add props/features "for future use" — implement when needed
- Don't duplicate logic across components — extract to `src/lib/` or the shared feature
